      {
        "heading": "The Method of Loci Connection",
        "content": "The Method of Loci (memory palace) is a 2,500-year-old technique used by Greeks, Romans, and medieval scholars. Memory champions use it to memorize thousands of items by placing them at locations. A meta-analysis by Twomey & Kroneisen (2021) across 13 randomized controlled trials showed a medium effect size for the technique. Crucially, Caplan et al. (2019) showed that Method of Loci effectiveness comes from placing items at locations — not from imagined navigation or visualization. Gridually externalizes this principle: instead of imagining a palace, you use a physical grid on screen. This makes it accessible to everyone, including people who can't visualize (aphantasia)."
