      {
        "heading": "Neuroscience Foundation",
        "content": "Spatial memory is primarily mediated by the hippocampus, particularly place cells (discovered by O'Keefe, Nobel Prize 2014) and grid cells (discovered by Moser & Moser, Nobel Prize 2014). These neurons create a cognitive map of space. When information is associated with spatial locations, it gains access to this powerful, evolutionarily ancient memory system. The hippocampus is also central to episodic memory formation, meaning spatial encoding creates richer, more contextual memories."
      },
      {
        "heading": "The Two-Stream Theory",
        "content": "Visual and spatial processing use separate brain pathways. Farah et al. (1988, Cognitive Psychology 20) demonstrated that visual (object) and spatial imagery are neurologically dissociable — processed through separate 'what' (ventral) and 'where' (dorsal) streams. Tresch et al. (1993, Neuropsychologia 31) confirmed this with a double dissociation: spatial interference only affects spatial memory, object interference only affects object memory. This is why spatial memory tools work even for people who cannot visualize: spatial encoding uses the dorsal 'where' stream, which is independent of visual imagery."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Research Evidence",
        "content": "Multiple studies support spatial memory for learning: (1) Legge et al. (2012) showed that the Method of Loci improved word list recall by 2-3x compared to rote memorization. (2) A meta-analysis by Dresler et al. (2017) found that spatial mnemonic strategies produced large effect sizes (d > 1.0) for memory performance. (3) Reggente et al. (2020) demonstrated that even virtual spatial environments improve factual learning compared to non-spatial interfaces."
      },
